          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">
          <strong>🇾🇪 Houthis free crew of cargo ship after 14 months in captivity. Release linked to support for Palestine.</strong> 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Yemen’s Houthi rebels <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-01-2025-br1-7-released-the-crew" target="_blank">released the crew</a> of the Galaxy Leader, a Bahamas-flagged vessel seized after 430 days. The 25 crew members are from several countries, including Bulgaria and the Philippines. They were handed to Oman following a ceasefire in Gaza. The Houthis linked the release to their support for Palestinians. However, they warned that they would go back to attacking ships if Israel broke the truce.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The ship was seized in November 2023 during a wave of Houthi maritime attacks that disrupted global shipping. The UN and maritime organizations welcome the release, calling it a “step in the right direction” and urging all nations to protect seafarers from becoming collateral damage in geopolitical conflicts. The Trump administration designated the Houthis as a terrorist group this week (<a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-01-2025-br2-8-executive-order" target="_blank">executive order</a>).</p>
        </mj-text>
